Theorem
\emph default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(a,n)>1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d:=\frac{n}{\gcd(a,n)}$
\end_inset

.
 (We know that this quotient is an integer less than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(a,n)\ |\ n$
\end_inset

.) Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(a,n)\ |\ a$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $c:=\frac{a}{\gcd(a,n)}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\gcd(a,n)\cdot c$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $da=\frac{n}{\cancel{\gcd(a,n)}}\cdot\cancel{\gcd(a,n)}\cdot c=nc\cong0\mod n$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

