\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a perfect square.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a+b\sqrt{n}:a,b\in\Z\}$
\end_inset

 is just 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z$
\end_inset

, which is already known to be a ring and a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is not a perfect square: now we have (a small amount of) work to do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $x:=x_{1}+x_{2}\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y:=y_{1}+y_{2}\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Subtraction closure.) Now 
\begin_inset Formula $x-y=(x_{1}-y_{1})+(x_{2}-y_{2})\sqrt{n}\in\{a+b\sqrt{n}:a,b\in\Z\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Multiplication closure.) But also 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=x_{1}y_{1}+nx_{2}y_{2}+(x_{1}y_{2}+x_{2}y_{1})\sqrt{n}\in\{a+b\sqrt{n}:a,b\in\Z\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

