 Proposition
\emph default
.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z[\sqrt{n}]$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Recall that an integral domain is a commutative ring with unity and no
 zero divisors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Commutative ring.) Multiplication of real numbers is commutative.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z[\sqrt{n}]$
\end_inset

 was established to be a ring in the previous proposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(With unity.) For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Z[\sqrt{n}]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $1x=x$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in\Z[\sqrt{n}]$
\end_inset

 because it's 
\begin_inset Formula $1+0\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(No zero divisors.) Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\Z[\sqrt{n}]$
\end_inset

 were such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then it would have to be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=0$
\end_inset

 in the superring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, but we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 has no zero divisors.
 Contradiction! 
